# Main Initial Statement
The reality of human-induced climate change is unequivocal, evidenced by an overwhelming body of scientific research and observation, as definitively stated by the IPCC's Sixth Assessment Report.  Failure to acknowledge this reality severely undermines effective mitigation and adaptation strategies.


## Supporting Points
1.  Human activities have unequivocally caused the observed increase in well-mixed greenhouse gas concentrations since 1750, leading to atmospheric, ocean, and land warming. {A.1.1}
2.  The scale of recent changes across the climate system is unprecedented over many centuries to many thousands of years, with the rate of global surface temperature increase since 1970 being faster than in any other 50-year period over at least the last 2000 years. {A.2, A.2.2}
3.  Human influence is the main driver of observed changes in numerous weather and climate extremes across the globe, including heatwaves, heavy precipitation, droughts, and tropical cyclones. {A.3}


## Evidence from Document
> "It is unequivocal that human influence has warmed the atmosphere, ocean and land. Widespread and rapid changes in the atmosphere, ocean, cryosphere and biosphere have occurred." {A.1.1}
> "Global surface temperature has increased faster since 1970 than in any other 50-year period over at least the last 2000 years (high confidence)." {A.2.2}


## Additional Context
- The IPCC report is a consensus document produced by leading climate scientists worldwide, representing the most comprehensive assessment of climate science available.
-  The report utilizes rigorous methods, including attribution studies, to assess the likelihood and attribution of observed changes to human influence.
-  The findings are supported by multiple lines of evidence from observations, paleoclimate data, and climate models.
